New Dutch Government Looks Set to Introduce Pro-Nuclear Policy.<br>
<br>
Energy officials in the Netherlands say the three centre-right parties that are now almost certain to form the next government have agreed in principle to fundamentally review the outgoing centre-left government’s negative attitude to nuclear energy. <br>
<br>
<br>
 <br>
They confirm stories in today’s major Dutch-language national newspapers, according to which the three parties reached a provisional agreement last night (Wednesday) to drop the outgoing government’s insistence on the premature closure of Borssele, the country’s only operational nuclear power plant. <br>
Such a decision would represent further evidence of a gradual swing back towards pro-nuclear political attitudes in Europe, in the wake of the Finnish parliament’s decision last week to authorise construction of a new nuclear power unit in Finland. <br>
The Dutch newspapers say the three parties – the Christian Democrats (CDA), the List Pim Fortuyn (LPF), and the Liberals (VVD) – agreed to allow continued operation of Borssele until at least 2007, and possibly until (or even beyond) the end of its current design life-time in 2013. <br>
While the reports have not yet been officially confirmed, officials at Borsselle operator EPZ and elsewhere say they are in line with previous statements attributed to leading party figures both before and since the general elections on 15th May. <br>
They say that, while coalition negotiations are still continuing, the clear parliamentary majority enjoyed by the three centre-right parties means that the main outlines of future government policy can already be defined relatively clearly. <br>
However, they point out that final policy declarations will have to be approved by parliament following the formation of a new government, which is not expected to be finalised for at least another four to six weeks. <br>
The new government is expected to be led by Jan Peter Balkenende of the CDA, whose party won 43 seats in the 150-seat parliament. The other two centre-right parties, the VVD and the LPF – founded by the flamboyant right-wing politician Pim Fortuyn, who was murdered shortly before the elections – won 24 and 26 seats respectively. <br>
Meanwhile, a ruling is expected shortly in a court case brought by the outgoing government, aimed at enforcing closure of Borssele by 2003, as narrowly agreed by parliament in 1994 . <br>
However, any decision to change government policy would mean that a negative outcome to the court case – from the point of view of the utility – would no longer have much practical significance. <br>
